      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers0565">
               <p>Charles was the eldest son of a wealthy sugar merchant <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers0568.xml"/>Peter Delamotte</persName> (d. <date
                     when="1749">1749</date>) of <placeName>Blendon Hall, Bexley</placeName>, and
                  his wife <persName><ref target="/persons/pers0567.xml"/>Elizabeth (Whickham)
                     Delamotte</persName> (<date from="1685" to="1771"
                  >1685–71</date><!-- Unsure if these are the right dates -->). Charles accompanied
                  the Wesley brothers on their voyage to <placeName>Georgia</placeName>, in
                  principle as his father&apos;s business agent. He was soon serving as schoolmaster
                  without remuneration, and assisting <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"
                     />JW</persName> in various pastoral duties. On his return to
                     <placeName>England</placeName>, a few months after <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>, he found that many of his
                  family had been converted to the emerging Methodist revival. Delamotte was more
                  drawn to the Moravian stream of the renewal and, on taking over the family
                  business, offered financial support to the work of <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers1121.xml"/>Benjamin Ingham</persName>. Even so, he
                  remained on friendly terms with <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"
                     />JW</persName>. See <hi rend="italic">DEB</hi>, 307–8; and Vickers, <hi
                     rend="italic">Dictionary</hi>, 92.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
